WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.126 --> 00:00:02.544
Some of the challenges we faced

00:00:02.544 --> 00:00:03.712
within Slack is

00:00:03.712 --> 00:00:05.463
traditionally information overload.

00:00:05.463 --> 00:00:07.007
One of our product principles is 

00:00:07.007 --> 00:00:08.216
be a great host.

00:00:08.216 --> 00:00:09.217
And so one of the things

00:00:09.217 --> 00:00:10.385
we wanted to help people with

00:00:10.385 --> 00:00:11.261
from the beginning,

00:00:11.261 --> 00:00:12.387
was actually distilling

00:00:12.387 --> 00:00:13.346
through the noise

00:00:13.346 --> 00:00:14.222
and actually figuring out

00:00:14.222 --> 00:00:15.306
what's important.

00:00:21.730 --> 00:00:22.939
When AI emerged,

00:00:22.939 --> 00:00:25.025
we had some very clear problems

00:00:25.025 --> 00:00:26.276
we wanted to solve.

00:00:26.276 --> 00:00:28.236
And those were specifically search

00:00:28.236 --> 00:00:29.154
and then summarizing

00:00:29.154 --> 00:00:30.822
high volumes of information.

00:00:30.822 --> 00:00:32.407
So we started to experiment with it,

00:00:32.407 --> 00:00:33.742
and with Claude in particular,

00:00:33.742 --> 00:00:34.993
and when we started to get

00:00:34.993 --> 00:00:36.494
our first search answers back,

00:00:36.494 --> 00:00:37.787
we saw like an immediate,

00:00:37.787 --> 00:00:39.664
almost like, mind meld with Claude

00:00:39.664 --> 00:00:41.207
that was our first

00:00:41.207 --> 00:00:43.126
holy cow moment.

00:00:43.126 --> 00:00:44.377
The system automatically

00:00:44.377 --> 00:00:45.628
takes care of answering

00:00:45.628 --> 00:00:46.504
things for me,

00:00:46.504 --> 00:00:48.006
summarizes information for me,

00:00:48.006 --> 00:00:49.424
and that just gives me minutes

00:00:49.424 --> 00:00:51.051
every single day.

00:00:51.051 --> 00:00:52.135
We track a number of

00:00:52.135 --> 00:00:53.386
metrics throughout Slack.

00:00:53.386 --> 00:00:54.554
One is query success rate.

00:00:54.554 --> 00:00:56.431
And two is the number of users that

00:00:56.431 --> 00:00:58.808
self-report Slack as feeling noisy

00:00:58.808 --> 00:00:59.476
and we've seen

00:00:59.476 --> 00:01:01.186
one of our biggest improvements

00:01:01.186 --> 00:01:03.063
with both of those metrics.

00:01:03.313 --> 00:01:04.981
Not only are we using Claude for

00:01:04.981 --> 00:01:07.067
some of our customer facing features

00:01:07.067 --> 00:01:09.069
but we're also using it with Claude Code

00:01:09.069 --> 00:01:11.112
to do things like fix bugs

00:01:11.112 --> 00:01:12.489
and really power teams

00:01:12.489 --> 00:01:14.157
internally to move faster.

00:01:14.157 --> 00:01:16.743
The limitation now is creativity

00:01:16.743 --> 00:01:17.660
and imagination.

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:19.621
It's not really a question

00:01:19.621 --> 00:01:21.456
of how to build the thing.

00:01:21.456 --> 00:01:22.582
It's a question of

00:01:22.582 --> 00:01:23.958
what do you want to build?

00:01:23.958 --> 00:01:25.251
Now I find myself

00:01:25.251 --> 00:01:26.503
spending a lot more time

00:01:26.503 --> 00:01:27.545
doing the planning

00:01:27.545 --> 00:01:30.131
and the architecture and less time

00:01:30.131 --> 00:01:32.217
actually coding up the solution.

00:01:32.217 --> 00:01:32.675
There's a lot more

00:01:32.675 --> 00:01:34.427
deep thinking going on.

00:01:34.427 --> 00:01:36.638
The benefits are largely time savings,

00:01:36.638 --> 00:01:37.514
and together with Claude,

00:01:37.514 --> 00:01:38.348
I think we could do something

00:01:38.348 --> 00:01:39.432
incredible to help people

00:01:39.432 --> 00:01:40.391
get even more

00:01:40.391 --> 00:01:41.559
throughout their days.

00:01:41.559 --> 00:01:42.602
This is the most excited

00:01:42.602 --> 00:01:43.895
I've been to be in technology

00:01:43.895 --> 00:01:45.605
in my entire career.

